{"type":"message","id":"1a839c2d","parentId":"2c083567","timestamp":"2026-05-20T06:52:53.882Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the issue!\n\nThe Chrome browser is running in **headless mode** (`--ozone-platform=headless`). This means it doesn't render to any display - it's a headless browser.\n\nThat's why:\n1. The screenshot shows a black image (headless mode doesn't render visually)\n2. The user can't see it on their VNC desktop\n\nThe Chrome process has:\n- `--ozone-platform=headless` - running in headless mode\n- `--headless=new` - also in headless mode\n- `--user-data-dir=/home/halei/.openclaw/browser/openclaw/user-data`\n- Remote debugging port: 18800\n- DISPLAY is empty (not set)\n\nBut there's X servers running (X1, X10) at `/tmp/.X11-unix/`. \n\nThe problem is Chrome is configured to run headless, not connected to any X display. For the user to see the browser via VNC, Chrome needs to run with a real X display (like X10 or whatever is available).\n\nTo fix this, I need to either:\n1. Set DISPLAY to point to the existing X server (X10 or X1) and restart the browser without headless mode\n2. Or use a different approach\n\nLet me check which X display is being used for VNC. The user said they're using VNC - so there should be an X server running that the user can see via VNC.\n\nLet me check what X display is available and which one might be the VNC session.\n","thinkingSignature":"02a45540697ccf8f3f8a2a8a9405de27f72af8451d3606ed31b4913ae735a299"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_8ywt7r77zgt3_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"ps aux | grep -i vnc | head -5 && echo \"---\" && w && echo \"---\" && ls -la /tmp/.X* 2>/dev/null"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":4717,"output":377,"cacheRead":78372,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":83466,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":17792