1vnc -display :1 -auth /run/user/1000/gdm/Xauthority -forever -shared -nopw -rfbport 5900 -bg\nhalei     392484  0.1  0.1 244788  7032 ?        S    13:56   0:05 /usr/bin/python3 /usr/bin/websockify --web /usr/share/novnc 6080 localhost:5900\nhalei     396603  0.0  0.0  13064  3672 ?        S    14:52   0:00 /bin/bash --noprofile --norc -c ps aux | grep -i vnc | head -5 && echo \"---\" && w && echo \"---\" && ls -la /tmp/.X* 2>/dev/null\nhalei     396605  0.0  0.0  12324  2608 ?        S    14:52   0:00 grep -i vnc\n---\n 14:52:53 up 10 days,  5:13,  1 user,  load average: 0.67, 0.70, 0.51\nUSER     TTY      来自           LOGIN@   IDLE   JCPU   PCPU WHAT\nhalei    :1       :1               13:55   ?xdm?   2:32m  0.00s /usr/libexec/gdm-x-session --run-script env GNOME_SHELL_SESSION_MODE=ubuntu /usr/bin/gnome-session --session=ubuntu\n---\n-r--r--r-- 1 halei halei   11  5月 10 09:39 /tmp/.X10-lock\n\n/tmp/.X11-unix:\n总计 36\ndrwxrwxrwt  2 root  root   4096  5月 20 13:55 .\ndrwxrwxrwt 74 root  root  28672  5月 20 14:51 ..\nsrwxrwxrwx  1 halei halei     0  5月 20 13:55 X1\nsrwxrwxrwx  1 halei halei     0  5月 10 09:39 X10\n\n/tmp/.XIM-unix:\n总计 36\ndrwxrwxrwt  2 root root  4096  5月 10 09:39 .\ndrwxrwxrwt 74 root root 28672  5月 20 14:51 ..","cwd":"/home/halei/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1779259974001}}
{"type":"message","id":"b68e8504","parentId":"bae13357","timestamp":"2026-05-20T06:53:15.959Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Interesting! I can see:\n\n1. VNC is running:\n   - `x11vnc -display :1` running on port 5900\n   - `websockify` on port 6080 (for noVNC)\n   \n2. There's a real X display (:1) running (not :0, which is the user's actual desktop)\n\n3. There's also X10-lock and an X10 socket, which might be the Chrome headless instance\n\nSo there are TWO X displays:\n- `:1` - This is where x11vnc is running (probably a real desktop session)\n- `:10` - This might be from Chrome headless\n\nBut wait - Chrome was started with `--ozone-platform=headless` which uses a virtual display. But the X10-lock and X10 socket suggest something is running on :10.\n\nLet me check if DISPLAY=:10 works for the browser. Actually, the Chrome process was started without an explicit DISPLAY setting (in the ps output I saw), so it probably inherited the environment. But wait, DISPLAY is empty in the output I got.\n\nActually, looking at the Chrome command line again:\n`/opt/google/chrome/chrome --remote-debugging-port=18800 ... --ozone-platform=headless`\n\nThe `--ozone-platform=headless` flag means it's using the Ozone/headless Chrome backend, which doesn't need a real X display. So it's running in headless mode without a DISPLAY.\n\nBut the user says they can see via VNC and they're connected to display :1. Let me check if Chrome was started with DISPLAY=:1 or if it's truly headless.\n\nActually, the problem is that OpenClaw's browser tool starts Chrome in headless mode (--headless=new --ozone-platform=headless), which means it doesn't render to any real X display. \n\nEven if I set DISPLAY=:1 when launching Chrome, headless mode bypasses the X server entirely. The screenshots I'm taking are from the headless instance, so the user won't see them through their VNC connection to the real desktop. To actually display Chrome in the VNC session, I'd need to either launch Chrome with DISPLAY=:1 without headless mode, or use a different approach that renders to the actual display.\n","thinkingSignature":"e9833c3a4916b79ae1dd79462c643d74e4fcbdd8d24bc03468a085c2e4233315"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_73cag9wclegs_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"ps aux | grep -E \"chrome|chromium\" | grep -v grep | head -5"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":4593,"output":517,"cacheRead":79235,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":84345,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1779259974181,"responseId":"065c8d466d314f6d6d9b642f85fefe33"}}
